This implies \( z_1 + z_2 = c \) and \( z_1 z_2 = 10 \). The vertices of the quadrilateral \( \mathcal{Q} \) are \( z_1 \), \( z_2 \), \( \frac{1}{z_1} \), and \( \frac{1}{z_2} \). To find the maximum area of \( \mathcal{Q} \), we use the shoelace formula for the area of a quadrilateral with vertices \( z_1, z_2, \frac{1}{z_1}, \frac{1}{z_2} \). Converting these vertices to coordinates, we have: - \( z_1 = a + bi \) - \( z_2 = a - bi \) - \( \frac{1}{z_1} = \frac{a}{10} - \frac{b}{10}i \) - \( \frac{1}{z_2} = \frac{a}{10} + \frac{b}{10}i \) Using the shoelace formula, the area \( A \) is calculated as: \[ A = \frac{1}{2} \left| \text{Im} \left( z_1 \overline{z}_2 + z_2 \overline{\left( \frac{1}{z_1} \right)} + \frac{1}{z_1} \overline{\left( \frac{1}{z_2} \right)} + \frac{1}{z_2} \overline{z}_1 \right) \right| \] Simplifying each term: - \( z_1 \overline{z}_2 = |z_1|^2 = 10 \) - \( z_2 \overline{\left( \frac{1}{z_1} \right)} = 1 \) - \( \frac{1}{z_1} \overline{\left( \frac{1}{z_2} \right)} = \frac{1}{10} \) - \( \frac{1}{z_2} \overline{z}_1 = 1 \) Summing these terms gives \( 10 + 1 + \frac{1}{10} + 1 = \frac{121}{10} \). The imaginary part is zero, but the area calculation using coordinates shows the area is maximized when \( |ab| \) is maximized. Given \( a^2 + b^2 = 10 \), the maximum \( |ab| \) is 5, achieved when \( a = \sqrt{5} \) and \( b = \sqrt{5} \). Thus, \( c = 2a = 2\sqrt{5} = \sqrt{20} \). Therefore, the value of \( m \) is \(\boxed{20}\).
